  I can't be responsible of any damage caused by the use of ATD.

@ENDNODE

@NODE TECHN "THE Technique :-)"

    @{b}Technical part@{ub}

  Hummm, now, it's a bit difficult. ATD deals with the double-double
  buffering technique. What's it ?? Easy : I've 4 Buffers for 1 animation
  (Yeah, 4 Buffers !!) and ATD load the first animation in the 2 first
  buffers (Bitmaps) and while the first anim is playing, ATD load the
  next anim in the 2 next buffers (buffers 3 and 4). Once the first anim is
  finished, ATD play the next anim without lost of time.

  If an anim is finished but the next anim isn't totally loaded, the playback
  will be stopped until the anim is finished to load.

  I Use an interruption for playback (The Vertical Blank interruption). By this
  way, the anim display is NEVER slowed or stopped BUT it could do some problems
  on slow Amigas, if a frame drawing take more than 1 VBlank (1/50 s).

  On my A1230/50, the anim playback is perfect. Like if the anim was played from
  Ram Disk (For standard Anim... Not Ham8 640*480 Anim :-).

  DrawBack of my system :

    + You MUST Split previously your animation into several part which
  can't execed 600 Kos by part.
    + You CAN't use DIFFERENTS SIZES for each anims. No.

@ENDNODE

@NODE REQUI "Requirement"

  @{b}Requirements@{ub}

    + An Amiga (Arf !)
    + Rom 2.04 +
    + An big IFF Animation (Hehe)
    + An Anim Splitter (DPaint or PPaint or...)
    + That's all man !

@ENDNODE

@NODE USEIT

  @{b}Using@{ub}

  First, you must have an animation. Convert it in SEVERAL PARTS of
  about 600 kos each (Yes, split your anim into several small anims
  IFF-Anim 5.) Just name your small anim with the SAME NAME and X at
  the end of the name :

      eg: You have a big anim called MyAnim.IFF
          + Split it into small anims that you call Anim1, Anim2,
            Anim3, Anim4,...

  @{b}NOTE: Each Sub-Anim can have it's own palette (could be good...)@{ub}

  ATD is a CLI ONLY utility. Type "AnimToDisk" or "AnimToDisk ?" to
  have a short help.

  The Arguments :

    <AnimName> : Must be the anim name. You anim MUST be like this :
  several part which name "NameAnim1", "NameAnim2", "NameAnimX" where
  X is the end of the anim. ADT will check if you files are correct
  during the playing. If an anim looks wrong, it will quit. Easy.
  The AnimName MUST be entered WITHOUT the last number (eg: "NameAnim"
  instead of "NamaAnim1")

    <Delay> : It's the delay between each frame.

      1=FASTEST PLAY (50 fps)

      50=One Frame is displayed each seconds (on PAL display)

      2= 25 fps

      4=12.5 fps

      Delay is OPTIONAL. If no delay is mentionned, a .5 (25 fps) delay
  will be take for default


      So, Now you know that ATD MUST have 4 buffers for his
  own diplaying. Ok, but these buffers take some place in
  chip mem. eg: if you want to playback an 256 colour 320*200
  anim (which could be easy with ATD :-) of 100 Mos (Splitted
  I meant :-) you need at least :

       320*200 ( <- Size of your anim)  /8 * 8 ( <- Bitplane number)
  = 64 kos * 4 (Because there are 4 buffers)
  = 256 kos.

  So 256 kos will be reserved for the buffers.

       Another exemple : 164*100 /8 *5 (yes, an 32 colour 164*100
  anim, you have guess :-)

  =11 kos * 4 = 44 kos of chip mem. CooL :-)

@ENDNODE

